For some years now I would run into my friend Marc Wierenga who co owns @signalsnowboard with his buddy Dave Lee . He would tell me about how they were making guitars out of cardboard . They work with a company called @ernest_packaging and have made snowboards out of cardboard in the past with them . Needless to say they’re the guru company for cardboard construction . Ran into marc again years later and he was telling me how they’ve been working and perfecting the cardboard Stratocaster with @fender senior master builder @paul_waller_fender and have included a cardboard p-bass along with cardboard drums crafted by Sahir Hanif . Also that they’ve started a series on YouTube called #cardboardsessions  where they get musicians to play these unique instruments in a studio setting . It’s been going for a year now and there’s a lot of really cool performances . Jmasic , John Reis , Jon Theodore , Isaiah Mitchell and Otis Barthoulamue to name a few . I recently had the privilege to play one finally with my long time friends @hiseyeshavefangs ( @thetonyalva1957 @bellaroi @jekyllandthehyde )who I’ve been enjoying playing with lately . We met up at @vans headquarters jam room and had a blast !!! wow who would of thought paper could sound good ? Guess Marc and Dave did . Hahaha biggest thnx for having us on board . Link to the vid in @cardboardsessions bio

this goofy 80s piece on this Seattle skate shop and the locals brings me back . People will ask what was skating like when you got into it . Well this pretty much represents a lot of the skate scenes that were happening then . Really just a bunch of kids excited about skating while gaining access into that world/culture via their local skate shop . during that time it wasn’t cool at all ,  people didn’t get it , ( kind of still don’t hahaha !!! ) you’d find yourself getting heckled and chased at times or maybe even something worse . crazy how that dynamic made me love it more . it was clear to me that if you knew then you knew and that created a huge sense of comradery that I really appreciated . Now a days skating is excepted and perceived in a much different way lending it’s self to a different kind of experience . This is reminding me of what a special time that was .

I’ve always been a big fan of the experimental music that was happening in west Germany in the late 60’s early 70’s . A mix of psychedelic rock , electronic music and avant-garde compositions with a lot of improvisation . Neu , Faust , Tangerine Dream , Kraftwerk , Cluster , Ash Ra Tempel , Popol Vuh , Amon Duu ll ,Harmonia and Can are the bands best known for the genre called krautrock . A term created by the British music press that had a derogatory tone but unfortunately stuck . Much like what happened to those early bands during the NY CBGB scene with the term punk .  At any rate a lot of great music came out of the genre . Dug how they moved away from the 60’ pop and R&B song structures of their day and incorporated early synth techniques like musique concrete and the use of hypnotic rhythms while fusing that with rock instrumentation .  This is footage of Can playing on BBC’s The Old Grey Whistle Test in 1975 . They’re one of my favorites from that scene .

This one from @girlskateboards goldfish video with @lancemountain along with his son and father doing a parody ( through pogo sticking ha )paralleling the life of a skater turning pro and loosing the enjoyment , is one of my favs . New @catpowerofficial live album Cat Power Sings Dylan The 1966 Royal Albert Hall Concert . A song by song recreation of the iconic performance that upset so many fans in attendance when halfway through he put down his acoustic , picked up his electric ,  brought out the band and cranked it up . Led to a lot of booing and heckling . But was such an important pivotal moment in his career .  I think this is a beautiful tribute to Bob in general but to that 1966 night in particular .
